# JSON üìã

**J**ava**S**cript **O**bject **N**otation is a lightweight data interchange format.

It is plain text written with object notation.

```javascript
// JS Object
const obj = { name: "John", age: 30 };

// Convert to JSON String
const myJSON = JSON.stringify(obj);
// '{"name":"John","age":30}'

// Parse JSON String back to Object
const newObj = JSON.parse(myJSON);
```

# Web Storage API üíæ

Allows you to store data locally within the user's browser.

## localStorage
Stores data with no expiration date.

```javascript
// Save
localStorage.setItem("lastname", "Smith");

// Retrieve
let name = localStorage.getItem("lastname");

// Remove
localStorage.removeItem("lastname");
```
**Note:** Values are always Strings!

# Geolocation API üìç

Locate the user's position.

```javascript
if (navigator.geolocation) {
  navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
} else {
  console.log("Geolocation is not supported.");
}

function showPosition(position) {
  console.log("Lat: " + position.coords.latitude);
  console.log("Long: " + position.coords.longitude);
}
```
Requires user permission.

# Async/Await with Fetch ü§ù

The modern way to call APIs.

```javascript
async function getUser() {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/user');
    if (!response.ok) {
      throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
    }
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error("Could not fetch user:", error);
  }
}
```
